  "prompt": "What is a microstrip antenna?",
  "response": "A microstrip antenna, also known as a patch antenna, is a low-profile, lightweight type of antenna commonly used in wireless communication systems. Here are its key characteristics:\n\n1. Structure:\n- Consists of a metallic patch (radiating element) mounted on a thin dielectric substrate\n- The patch is typically made of copper or other conductive material\n- A ground plane is located on the opposite side of the substrate\n\n2. Design characteristics:\n- Flat and compact\n- Lightweight\n- Low profile\n- Easy to fabricate\n- Relatively low cost\n\n3. Operating principles:\n- Radiation occurs from the edges of the metallic patch\n- Electromagnetic waves are generated through the substrate\n- Can be designed for various frequencies and polarizations\n\n4. Common applications:\n- Wireless communication devices\n- Satellite communication\n- Mobile phones\n- GPS systems\n- Radar systems\n- Wireless networks\n\n5. Advantages:\n- Conformable to planar and non-planar surfaces\n- Simple and inexpensive to manufacture\n- Can be easily integrated with microwave circuits\n\n6. Limitations:\n- Relatively low gain\n- Narrow bandwidth\n- Relatively low efficiency compared to other antenna types",
